Did you know I am a 2xs breast cancer survivor? Swipe left you will see I lost all of my hair during treatment when I was diagnosed in 2016. 3 years in remission, my hair grew to my mid-back. After being diagnosed for the 2nd time in 2019, I cried so hard because I knew the process and knew I was going to lose my hair. 
I received information from a young lady that was going through treatment, there’s a way to retain my hair. 
It’s called “Cold Capping.” 
What is cold capping? 
It’s a process where you place -33 degree or lower on your scalp for 30 minutes while going through treatment. The caps are switched out every 30 minutes on your head to restrict the follicles and prevents the treatment from getting to your scalp. The caps are kept in a cooler with dry ice and the process continues up to 2 hours after treatment. 
I was able to obtain the gel caps from a company known as @penguincoldcapsglobal and @hairtostayorg assisted with funding coverage.
This process allowed me to retain 80% of my hair. Of course I’ve experienced shedding but I am forever graceful for this process and these two companies were introduced to me. 🙏🏾🙏🏾🙏🏾

Do you have moments when you want to give up? 
A little back story about myself and Jsincorporated. I have experienced so many ups and downs when it comes to this business. There has been so many times I’ve thrown in the towel. I would tell myself, “this is not for me” I would ask God to send me a sign that I’m on the right path with this business. And I promise you, each and every time a order pings my phone 📱! I had to tell myself, you will have your moment. You will have your break through. The timing of everyone’s hardship is different. Some people hardships last for 3 months, some last for 5 years maybe even 10, but they don’t give up. If it’s a challenge, it’s worth fighting for. So we’re on the season of pushing through even when we don’t won’t to. Walk by faith and not by sight.

Thank you @mercy_health for using @jsincorporated in recognition of ovarian cancer awareness month. 
Refillable awareness ribbons are available and can be filled with different colors to bring awareness to each month. 

Signs of Ovarian cancer: 

Pain areas: in the abdomen or pelvis
Gastrointestinal: bloating, change in bowel habits, indigestion, or nausea
Abdominal: abdominal fullness, fluid in the abdomen, or lump in the abdomen
Whole body: cancer-related fatigue or loss of appetite
Also common: weight loss

Don’t ignore the signs ladies, seek health advise if you have any concerns.

As October comes to an end I would like to share my journey as a breast cancer survivor. I was diagnosed in 2016 with staged 2 lobular breast cancer. The news was devastating. I was only 27 years old. I remember my doctor saying as I sobbed, “ there’s a light at the end of the tunnel, and I am going to get you there.!” I looked up and said, “ let’s go, I’m ready to get back to my life!” I’ve learned so much through my first journey, that it prepared me for my second fight! I was diagnosed with the same exact cancer in the same breast in 2019. This time the journey wasn’t as detrimental. I was able to keep my hair and with the tips I’ve retained from the previous journey, I was able to take on those side effects with less complications. People including my doctors were so astonished about my strength and will power. I receive so many inquires and questions everyday about my journey and how did I do it. I decided to create a journal | planner to help those through their journey. Treatment comes so fast it doesn’t allow you to accept the fact, “You have breast cancer!” I’ve developed organizational skills through my journey because I was my own advocate. The journal | planner includes tips that will help during chemotherapy, radiation, and surgery. There’s a Calendar to stay organized for appointments and medications. A notes section to record answers you receive from your doctors. Also a journal that will allow you to express your frustrations and uplift you throughout your journey.
-I truly hope this will be helpful for anyone who has to embark on this journey. I didn’t have anything as such and had to learn through the process. 
-There’s a Link in the bio to access the journal | planner
I love you all!! May God continue to protect us 💕🎀

“My Breast Cancer Journey Journal | Planner” was created 2 months ago. Since I’ve launch and promoted this Journal | Planner, I haven’t  received not 1 sale. Coming from a 2x breast cancer survivor, I put all my knowledge into this planner | journal that would help others as they embark on that journey of kicking cancer a$$! It’s filled with tips that would help through chemo, surgery, and radiation. A lot of information that no one would have to go looking for. Women are able to stare cancer down with confidence knowing they can beat this! The journal allows you to let out all your anger and frustration. I didn’t have an outlet, and the outcome, after all the smoke cleared was therapy. But therapy was a gift that I thought I never needed. The planner helps you stay organized with your medication and doctors appointment. Other survivors can attest, when you are first diagnosed, you don’t have room to breathe. Everything is on go!!!! The process moves so fast. A week after I got diagnosed, I had surgery to receive my port for administering the chemo during treatment. Chemo was the following week! 😱 I had no room to process the fact “I had cancer.” My organization skills didn’t develop until after my first treatment. I remember walking into treatment and the nurse asked me where’s my medication that I had to take the day of treatment. Shit I forgot, I already had to take medication a day before. Like I said, I didn’t have time to even process anything let alone be organized. So they had to go in the medication room and provide the medication. That’s when it hit me, oh honey you have to get your shit together. I became so organized, it trickled down to my lifestyle. But if I had this in the beginning, I know I would of handled everything with a breeze. It would have been my best friend. Well 2 days ago a survivor ordered the journal. The “cha Ching” notification caught me off guard and I thought it was an order for the toppers. When I seen it was an order for the journal | planner I was ecstatic but nervous at the same time. I want this journal | planner to be very helpful to people. Then yesterday, I received a notification that she left a review! ⬆️ 🙏🏾
